cial-format:bullet"><li><i>Cut to the JPMChase</i>: I wanted to start with =
a brief note to my influential readers at JPMorgan Chase, which is on track=
 to make around $52 billion in net income this year, regarding the customer=
 experience at America=E2=80=99s largest bank. One reason JPM makes so much=
 money
these days is by paying its depositors almost nothing=E2=80=94.01 percent o=
n their checking accounts and .02 percent on their savings accounts=E2=80=
=94for the use of their money, which obviously is lent out at much, <i>much=
</i> higher rates of interest. This arbitrage is referred to as =E2=80=9Cne=
t interest income=E2=80=9D in the bank=E2=80=99s income statement. In the s=
econd quarter, JPM made nearly $23 <i>billion</i> in =E2=80=9Cnet interest =
income=E2=80=9D alone.<br/><br/>Like millions of other depositors, I=E2=80=
=99ve stuck with Chase=E2=80=94and have, for four decades=E2=80=94in part b=
ecause of the perception that the bank has a =E2=80=9Cfortress balance shee=
t,=E2=80=9D as <b>Jamie Dimon </b>likes to say, and is also seen as =E2=80=
=9Ctoo big to fail=E2=80=9D and also because inertia is a very powerful for=
ce. But have the rigid steps the bank takes in the name of protecting its d=
epositors gone too far? The thought crossed my mind when I tried to wire my=
 own money for a capital call to a private equity firm I=E2=80=99ve been do=
ing business with for nearly 20
years=E2=80=94only for the transfer to be denied over and over (and over) a=
gain.  <br/><br/>After much identity checking, I was told to try to send th=
e wire again, after waiting 20 minutes, and that it would go through, no pr=
